just a short note to correct something:
You can get hypnotized unknowingly, so technically without consent.

this happened to a (i think german?) man who shared a room with someone in prison, his co-inmate "hypnotized" him over a period of time, "programming" him to rob a bank and shoot a specific person as soon as he would recieve a specific trigger.
the hypnosis-victim did that and only after the deed realized what he had done, he remembered what happened vaguely, and turned himself in to the police until the investigators figured out the whole hypnosis thing becouse they noticed the person who had been shot was the ex of the former co-inmate. the former co-inmate admitted what he had done to the victim later.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm not going to lie that part where Mark said he hated his younger self really resonated with me, but for entirely different reasons. When I think of my younger self, I tend to see you two versions. The one who doesn't come up as much is me as a kid. I don't really hate them oh, but I do pity him. I pity him because I know the potential he has and that he is going to be hot not to achieve it, and just going to let himself be taught not to cheat on top of that combined and exceedingly large lack of self-awareness, or awareness of any kind... And I can't help but pity the small child, who for the longest time was so unaware of his own body oh, that he fought the entire world was a third person video game. Then there's teenage me, the one that I despise with every fiber of my being. He was every bad male stereotype. he would treat other people as objects, not just women. He would constantly compare himself to others, but never really looked at people for what they were were, he would just find what the world considered good, and compare it to him just to belittle himself. And I think that is the main reason I hate him. That attitude with the world revolved around him. That because of this thing that he never asked for it was just born with, the world owed him a favor. It owed him for feeling him a weakness that's made both him and everyone around him assume he would fail. and I still deal with his bulshit today. I'm starting to learn to forgive him, and to let go of my hatred for my autism and if any of the people I wronged somehow see this , if you even vaguely remember me or if I truly traumatized you... I am sincerely sorry I hope you can forgive me but let's be honest there's no excuse for what I did. Regardless I want you to know that if I could oh, I would go back in time oh, and throw myself in a ditch to prevent what happened.

snippet.textDisplay:
Serious story here for a second. Before I was officially diagnosed with bipolar depression, I was searching for a therapist. My mom took me to a hypnotherapist that was recommended to her for me. I remember her office very well. My mom came with me and we were talking about the "procedure" or what I hope to accomplish or address, and the therapist gave me a paper form to fill out while she talked to my Mom. One of the things on the form was asking about "what is something you have noticed you are becoming increasingly afraid of, if there is such thing." I remember asking and confirming with the therapist, "My mom isn't going to see this, right?"

So my Mom had left and the lady turned all the lights down, and I was in a chair just like the women in the video had, and we tried addressing my soda addition (which is still an actual problem, considering I have severe acid reflux and lost my gallbladder because of soda). After all was said and done I told her that I don't feel anything she did helped at all.

She told me she wasn't expecting it to. I was kind of annoyed and confused at that. We were already tight on money, my mom was especially, so why did this lady knowingly waste my mom's money? She told me she knew before we started that we weren't going to accomplish anything today because what I wrote on that paper. She said because of what I wrote, I was going to be distracted, and would try to use this "stop my soda addiction" thing as a test to see if this would really work, and if it did I could then really conquer the fear I had written down.


I had written down that I think I'm realizing I'm gay, and I don't want to be. I was afraid there was no changing it.

In the end she was right. The soda thing didn't work because I didn't care if it worked, I was too concerned about convincing myself that this lady can help me magically not be gay. But you don't get to decide if you're gay, so, she can't "fix" that. She could only make me come to terms with it, which I didn't want to do. That's the whole "allow yourself" thing about hypnosis.

In hindsight, that was really an experience that made me feel doomed. I did come to terms with being gay a few months later but not in a positive way. I was bulled severely up until my sophomore year in high school, even attempting suicide in middle school. I just wanted to be "normal" and blend in, but nothing I did ever let me do that. And now I have being gay, to add to that?


Anyway, wrapping this up, my point is that you may look at this video and think this whole thing is silly. You may even go try it for yourself. You may only have one, hour long, session like me and think that nothing got done and it was a waste of time. But it's a really different type of therapy, and it might end up helping you grasp something you were otherwise unable to, if you let it.
